🎯 Interview Favorite Questions
Difference between Image & Container
Image	Container
Blueprint	Running instance
Read-only	Writable layer
Used to create container	Executes application
What is Multi-Stage Build?

Multi-stage builds allow separating build environment and runtime environment.

Example:

FROM node:20 AS builder
RUN npm install

FROM node:20-alpine
COPY --from=builder /app .

Benefits:

Smaller image

Secure

Faster deployments

Why Use Distroless Images?

Distroless images contain only runtime dependencies.

Benefits:

Smaller size

No shell access

Reduced attack surface

Example:

FROM gcr.io/distroless/python3
What is BuildKit?

BuildKit is modern Docker build engine.

Benefits:

Faster builds

Parallel execution

Better caching

Enable:

export DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1
What is Non-Root Container?

Running application as non-root user improves security.

Example:

RUN groupadd -r appgroup && useradd -r -g appgroup appuser

USER appuser

Benefits:

Prevent privilege escalation

Safer production containers

Difference between COPY & ADD
COPY	ADD
Basic file copy	Extra features
Recommended	Less predictable
No auto extract	Can extract archives

Best practice:

Always use COPY
What is Docker Layer Caching?

Docker caches each build step.

Example:

COPY package.json .
RUN npm install

If code changes but dependencies don't → Docker reuses cached layer.

This makes builds much faster.

What is Build Context?

Build context = files sent to Docker daemon during build.

Example:

docker build .

. = current directory is context.

Docker can only access files inside context.

CMD vs ENTRYPOINT
CMD	ENTRYPOINT
Default command	Fixed command
Can override	Hard to override

Example:

CMD ["python","app.py"]
